<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="216" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[831,1437,1250,1595]" pageId="13" pageNumber="216">
Saussure (1860) gave a more detailed description of both sexes, although based on apparently immature specimens. The MHNG collection has two dry specimens under the name 
<taxonomicName box="[894,1085,1347,1370]" class="Diplopoda" family="Xystodesmidae" genus="Fontaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="13" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="otomitus">
<emphasis box="[894,1085,1347,1370]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="216">Fontaria otomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. One is card-mounted and has the label “♀ Puebla, Mexique, M H de Saussure,” the other is directly pinned with a small piece of card supporting the centre of the specimen and is unlabelled. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoffman R. L." bookContentInfo="584 pp." box="[1264,1437,1442,1467]" journalOrPublisher="Virginia Museum of Natural History, Martinsville" pageId="13" pageNumber="216" refString="Hoffman R. L. 1999. Checklist of the millipeds of North and Middle America. Special Publication No. 8. Virginia Museum of Natural History, Martinsville. 584 pp." title="Checklist of the millipeds of North and Middle America. Special Publication No. 8" type="book" year="1999">Hoffman (1999)</bibRefCitation>
stated that he had only found one immature ♂ in the MHNG, it is unclear whether this refers to the unlabelled specimen. Both specimens are presumably syntypes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
